body:
The logic after transforming with verilator is not the same as original RTL code;

Example:
example is edited based on verilator/examples/make_tracing_sc/top.v; just replace top.v with the code below and then input command "make" (add verilator_flags  --Wno-fatal).

=============================================================
// top.v
module top
  (
   // Declare some signals so we can see how I/O works
   input              clk,
   input              fastclk,
   input              reset_l,

   output wire [1:0]  out_small,
   output wire [39:0] out_quad,
   output wire [69:0] out_wide,
   input [1:0]        in_small,
   input [39:0]       in_quad,
   input [69:0]       in_wide
   );

   // Connect up the outputs, using some trivial logic
   assign out_small = ~reset_l ? '0 : (in_small + 2'b1);
   assign out_quad  = ~reset_l ? '0 : (in_quad + 40'b1);
   assign out_wide  = ~reset_l ? '0 : (in_wide + 70'b1);

   // And an example sub module. The submodule will print stuff.
   sub sub (/*AUTOINST*/
            // Inputs
            .clk                        (clk),
            .fastclk                    (fastclk),
            .reset_l                    (reset_l));

   // Print some stuff as an example
   initial begin
      $display("[%0t] Model running...\n", $time);
   end

// ============add code start=====================
parameter row=15;
parameter col=9;

reg [row:0][col:0]  seg_chunk_num_pre;
reg [row:0][col:0]  seg_chunk_num;
reg [row:0][col:0]  seg_chunk_num_flip;

integer k;
always @(posedge fastclk) begin
    if (reset_l)
		for (k=0; k<row+1; k=k+1) begin
			seg_chunk_num_pre[k] <= 10'b0;
		end
	else
		for (k=0; k<row+1; k=k+1) begin
			seg_chunk_num_pre[k] <= 10'b1 + k;
		end
end	

integer i;
always @(*) begin
	for (i=0; i<row+1; i=i+1) begin
		seg_chunk_num[i] = seg_chunk_num_pre[i];
		seg_chunk_num_flip[i] = seg_chunk_num[row-1-i];
	end
end	
// ============add code end=====================

endmodule

=============================================================


Waveform:
Ideally seg_chunk_num_flip should be changed simultaneouslly after seg_chunk_num being changed;
but the waveform shows that parts of bits of seg_chunk_num_flip is changed at next clk posedge, which is not the original logic of RTL code!
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/120101215/222698467-263759f5-a621-416d-adc9-a7624ead9282.png)

Besides, if the order of code is reversed. such as code below: The waveform will be fine. 
		//seg_chunk_num[i] = seg_chunk_num_pre[i];
		seg_chunk_num_flip[i] = seg_chunk_num[row-1-i];
                seg_chunk_num[i] = seg_chunk_num_pre[i];

verilator version:  verilator-master;  downloaded 2023/03/03
OS: CentOS 6.10
